type: text/vnd.tiddlywiki

An ''axis'' is a reusable derive-key spec — a filter that maps each tiddler to a bucket key (a year, a status, the first tag, anything). A channel can chain several axes to build a grouped tree:

''year → month → day → tiddlers in that day''.

Each axis runs at one tree depth. Drilling into a bucket narrows the source set to rows whose key matches the bucket, then re-enters at the next axis.

! Where to find it

* ''Pick a grouped view:'' Tab into the view strip, switch to ''By date'' — the shipped demo (axes: year → month → day, no children).
* ''Edit any channel's chain in-place:'' Tab to the ''Structure'' strip, press Enter / → to expand. Each channel's mini-row shows its current chain as yellow ''by'' / ''→'' pills, ending in a dashed ''+''. The strip is hidden when there are no pills to show.

! Editing the chain

|!Gesture |!Effect |
|''Backspace'' / ''Delete'' on a focused axis pill |Remove that axis from the chain |
|''Shift-←'' / ''Shift-→'' on a focused axis pill |Reorder within the chain |
|''Enter'' on a focused axis pill |Open the picker in ''replace'' mode |
|''Enter'' / ''Space'' on the ''+'' pill |Open the picker in ''append'' mode |
|''Esc'' in the picker |Cancel — no change to the chain |

The picker is itself a cascade stage listing every axis registered in the wiki. On commit, the new chain is written to a session-state tiddler — survives reload, but isn't filesystem-synced. Delete that state tiddler to revert the channel to its declared default.

! Axes vs. children — one descent, two halves

|!Channel has |!Result |
|axes only |Pure grouping. Buckets all the way down; deepest buckets contain tiddler leaves. |
|children only |Today's recursive tree (''By parent'', ''By namespace''). Axes never engage. |
|axes + children |Buckets at the top, recursive tree at the bottom. E.g. "TOC tiddlers grouped by year, each TOC then expanding its tag-subtree." |
|neither |Flat list of `roots`. |

The two never fight: axes own the top of the tree, children owns the bottom. The transition happens at the depth where the chain runs out — that's the only place they meet, in the leaf-detection check (''does `children` return anything under this tiddler?'').

! Shipped axes

<$list filter="[all[shadows+tiddlers]tag[$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/axis]sort[ca-axis-name]]" variable="axis">|`<$view tiddler=<<axis>> field="ca-axis-name"/>` |<$view tiddler=<<axis>> field="ca-axis-hint"/> |
</$list>

! Authoring your own

Tag a tiddler `$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/axis` with at minimum a `ca-axis-name` and a `ca-axis-key` filter:

```
title: $:/plugins/example/axes/by-first-tag
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/axis
ca-axis-name: First tag
ca-axis-key: [tags[]first[]]
ca-axis-sort: asc
ca-axis-empty-label: untagged
```

The next palette open picks it up. Attach it to a channel via `ca-channel-axes` (or `ca-view-axes` on an implicit-channel view) — space-separated tiddler titles, in chain order.

''→'' Full axis schema + composition rules: <$link to="$:/plugins/rimir/cascade-palette/doc/protocol">doc/protocol</$link> (Axes section).
